Vulnerability Name: Vertical Privilege Escalation  
Severity: High
Objective: To get the admin access inside the web application and perform unauthorized administrative work.
Impact: The attacker/or a normal user with no admin rights can get full access to the admin page and perform unauthorized administrative action.
OWASP Category: A01:2025 – Broken Access Control
Vulnerable Parameter: Admin parameter
Vulnerability Description: The application relied on a client-side request parameter to determine administrative privileges. By intercepting and modifying the request, elevated privileges were obtained without proper server-side authorization checks.
Methodology:
Step 1 – User Authentication
        Logged into the application using the provided user credentials.
Step 2 - Traffic Analysis
        Next the traffic was taken into Burp Suite and the request parameters were inspected thoroughly.
        It was observed that the admin parameter was set to false.
Step 3 - Parameter Manipulation
        The request was now modified from admin= false to admin=true.
Step 4 - Authorization Validation
        This modified request was forwarded and the application was refreshed to check any changes.
Step 5 - Result
        The logged in normal user with no admin rights was not able to access the admin panel and make changes to it.

Remediation: 
Never trust privilege values received from client requests.
Implement role-based access control.
Every endpoint request for authorization should be validated from server side before forwarding.
Never use user-modifiable parameters.

Key Learning: 
Decisions defining privilege should be verified on the server side and it should never use user-modifiable parameters.


